HTB Pterodactyl - Privilege Escalation Write-up
🛡️ Security Assessment Report: Pterodactyl
1. Executive Summary
During a security assessment of the Pterodactyl host, a critical privilege escalation chain was identified. By combining a vulnerability in the PAM environment configuration (CVE-2025-6018) with a logic flaw in the UDisks2 service (CVE-2025-6019), a local unprivileged user can gain full root access.

2. Vulnerability Details
Vulnerability A: PAM Environment Injection (CVE-2025-6018)
Type: Environment Variable Injection

Severity: Medium

Description: The system allows users to define environment variables in ~/.pam_environment. This can be used to override critical session variables (like XDG_SEAT or DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS) which influence the behavior of privileged daemons.

Vulnerability B: UDisks2 Authorization Bypass (CVE-2025-6019)
Type: Logic Flaw / Privilege Escalation

Severity: High

Description: When udisks2 processes requests from a session that claims to be "local" and "active" via spoofed environment variables, it fails to properly validate Polkit authorizations, allowing unauthorized mount operations.



